    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Uniform-Convergence">
        <title>Uniform Convergence</title>
        
        <p>
            The second example shows that if a sequence of continuous functions converges pointwise to a limit function, the limit function is not necessarily a continuous function.
        </p>

        <p>
            Cauchy 1821: Theorem that if a sum of continuous functions converges then the limit function is continuous.
        </p>

        <p>
            Abel 1826: Cauchy's theorem admits exceptions such as <m>\sin \phi -\frac{1}{2} \sin 2\phi + \frac{1}{3} \sin 3\phi - \ldots</m> , which is discontinuous at every value of <m>(2m+1)\pi</m> , where <m>m</m>  is an integer.
        </p>

        <p>
            It has been argued; however, that Cauchy's theorem is not wrong and that Cauchy knew about Abel's exception but it is not a counterexample to his theorem.
        </p>

        <p>
            The issue involves what did Cauchy mean by a convergent sum. Abel interpreted Cauchy's theorem as pointwise convergence, which is false as his exception shows.
        </p>

        <p>
            However, Cauchy may have meant for convergence to mean a stronger type than pointwise convergence, which today is called uniform convergence.
        </p>

        <p>
            Abel's exception is not uniformly convergent and thus would not be a counterexample to Cauchy's theorem. In fact, Cauchy's theorem is correct if the convergence is uniform convergence.
        </p>

        <p>
            Before introducing the definition of uniform convergence, let's restate the definition of pointwise convergence in terms of <m>\epsilon</m> .
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-pointwise-convergence-epsilon">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>(f_n)</m>  be a sequence of functions defined on a set <m>A \subseteq \mathbf{R}</m> . Then <m>(f_n)</m>  converges pointwise on <m>A</m>  to a limit <m>f</m>  defined on <m>A</m>  if, for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>  and <m>x \in A</m> , there exists <m>N(\epsilon,x) \in \mathbf{N}</m>  (perhaps dependent on <m>x</m> ) such that <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)| &lt; \epsilon</m>  whenever <m>n \geq N</m> .
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>
         Notice that the choice of <m>N</m>  may depend on the point <m>x</m> .
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-uniform-convergence">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>(f_n)</m>  be a sequence of functions on a set <m>A \subseteq \mathbf{R}</m> . Then <m>(f_n)</m>  converges uniformly  on <m>A</m>  to a limit function defined on <m>A</m>  if for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>  there exists <m>N(\epsilon) \in \mathbf{N}</m>  such that <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)|&lt; \epsilon</m>  whenever <m>n \geq N</m>  and <m>x \in A</m> .
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>
            The difference between uniform and convergence and pointwise convergence is that in uniform convergence for each <m>\epsilon>0</m>  a single <m>N</m>  must work for all <m>x \in A</m>  while in pointwise convergence for each <m>\epsilon &gt;0</m>  and <m>x \in A</m>  different choices of <m>N</m>  may be used.
        </p>

        <p>
            Let <m>f_n(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{n}</m> . Show that <m>f_n(x)</m>  converges uniformly to <m>0</m>  on <m>\mathbf{R}</m> .
        </p>

