<p>
            We saw that the sequence <m>g_n(x) = x^n</m>  converges pointwise on <m>[0,1]</m>  to
            <md>
                g(x) = \begin{cases} 
      \hfill 0 \amp \text{ if $ 0 \leq x &lt; 1$ } \\
      \hfill  1 \hfill \amp \text{ if $x = 1$ }
                        \end{cases} 
            </md>
            
        </p>

        <p>
            Let's show that this sequence does not converge uniformly on <m>[0,1]</m> . For this, suppose <m>0 &lt; x &lt; 1</m>  and <m>0 &lt; \epsilon &lt; 1</m> .
        </p>

        <p>
            If the convergence was uniform then we would be able to find <m>N(\epsilon) \in \mathbf{N}</m>  depending only on <m>\epsilon</m>  such that <m>|g_n(x)-g(x)| &lt; \epsilon</m>  when <m>n \geq N</m> . But
            <md>
                |g_n(x)-g(x)| = |x^n-0| = x^n
            </md>
            
        </p>

        <p>
            If <m>x^n &lt; \epsilon</m>  then
            <md>
                <mrow> \ln(x^n) &lt; \amp \ln(\epsilon)</mrow>
                <mrow> n \ln(x) &lt; \amp \ln(\epsilon) </mrow>
                <mrow> n &gt; \amp \frac{\ln(\epsilon)}{\ln(x)} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            But this means that <m>n</m>  depends on the choice of <m>x</m>  (note that as <m>x\to 1^-</m> , <m>n \to \infty</m> ) and thus the convergence is not uniform.
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Uniform-Convergence-and-Continuity">
        <title>Uniform Convergence and Continuity</title>
        <p>
            In the two examples of sequences of continuous functions that converge to a limit function that is not continuous, the convergence has been pointwise convergence but not uniform convergence. In fact, if a sequence of continuous functions converges uniformly, then the limit function will also be continuous.
        </p>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-Continuous-Limit">
            <title>Continuous Limit Theorem</title>
            
            
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>(f_n)</m> be a sequence of functions defined on <m>A \subseteq \mathbf{R}</m> that converges uniformly on <m>A</m> to a function <m>f</m>. If each <m>f_n</m> is continuous at <m>c \in A</m>, then <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>

        <proof>
            <p>
                Let <m>c \in A</m> be fixed and let <m>\epsilon &gt;0</m>. It follows from the definition of uniform continuity that there exists <m>N(\epsilon)\in \mathbf{N}</m> such that <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)| &lt; \epsilon</m> whenever <m>n \geq N</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Because <m>f_N</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>, there exists <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> such that <m>|f_N(x)-f_N(c)| &lt; \epsilon</m> whenever <m>|x-c| &lt;\delta</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                We want to show that <m>|f(x)-f(c)|</m> can be made arbitrarily small by choosing <m>|x-c|</m> sufficiently small.
            </p>

            <p>
                Putting this all together we get that if <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m>
                <md>
                    <mrow> |f(x)-f(c)| \amp = |f(x)-f_N(x) + f_N(x) -f_N(c)+f_N(c)-f(c)|</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp \leq |f(x)-f_N(x)| + |f_N(x)-f_N(c)| + |f_N(c)-f(c)| </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp &lt; \epsilon + \epsilon + \epsilon = 3\epsilon</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Since <m>\epsilon</m> can be made arbitrarily small, so can <m>3\epsilon</m> and thus <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>

        <p>
            Something to consider: If convergence is only pointwise, where does the proof break down?
        </p>

        
        
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Cauchy">
        <title>Cauchy Criterion</title>

        <p>
            There is a Cauchy criterion for uniform convergence similar to the one for sequences.
        </p>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-Cauchy-Criterion">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A sequence of functions <m>(f_n)</m> converges uniformly on <m>A</m> if and only if for every <m>\epsilon>0</m> there exists <m>N(\epsilon) \in \mathbf{N}</m> such that <m>|f_n(x)-f_m(x)| &lt; \epsilon</m> whenever <m>m,n \geq N</m> and <m>x \in A</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        
    </subsection>


    </section>